To be fair, it would be really hard to design a dictionary-based machine learning program that wouldn't have false positives while still being at least reasonably effective. The chances of one person having enough false positives to constitute a punishment due to false positives alone - statistically speaking - not going to happen, not one in ten million. Everyone can afford to have one, factually speaking.
{{champion:1}} 
How dare you say "should".
